        introduction: "Besançon is one of France's most beautiful fortified cities, historic capital of Franche-Comté and prefecture of the Doubs. Enclosed within an almost perfect meander of the Doubs forming a loop 250 metres in diameter, the old town is dominated by the formidable Vauban Citadel, inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2008 as part of Vauban's fortifications. This 11-hectare citadel, built between 1668 and 1683, is Franche-Comté's most visited monument with 280,000 visitors a year: it houses three museums, a zoo, an insectarium, an aquarium and a noctarium. Besançon is also France's watchmaking capital since the 18th century: the Time Museum, housed in the Granvelle Palace, traces this centuries-old tradition. The city was the birthplace of Victor Hugo (1802) and the Lumière brothers (1862 and 1864). Taxis from Dijon are popular with tourists visiting the citadel, business travellers, academics (Besançon has 30,000 students) and winter sports enthusiasts heading to Jura ski resorts.",
